,"1070–1125":"1070–1125","1070–1139":"1070–1139","1075–1132":"1075–1132","1090–Female":"1090–Afdød","1110–Female":"1110–Afdød","1044–1105":"1044–1105","1048–1095":"1048–1095","1090":"1090","1044":"1044","1110":"1110","1132":"1132","1065":"1065","1064":"1064","1075":"1075","1162":"1162","1095":"1095","1070":"1070","1118":"1118","1139":"1139","1105":"1105","1048":"1048","1125":"1125","1067":"1067","about 1067":"omkring 1067","Llys Y Coed, Flintshire, Wales":"Llys Y Coed, Flintshire, Wales","Tegaingl, Flintshire, Wales":"Flintshire, Wales","Wales":"Wales","Flintshire, Wales":"Flintshire, Wales, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"about 1067–1118":"circa 1067–1118","1065–1162":"1065–1162","1067–1118":"1067–1118","1070–1125":"1070–1125","1070–1139":"1070–1139","1075–1132":"1075–1132","1090–Female":"1090–Overleden","1110–Female":"1110–Overleden","1044–1105":"1044–1105","1048–1095":"1048–1095","1090":"1090","1044":"1044","1110":"1110","1132":"1132","1065":"1065","1064":"1064","1075":"1075","1162":"1162","1095":"1095","1070":"1070","1118":"1118","1139":"1139","1105":"1105","1048":"1048","1125":"1125","1067":"1067","about 1067":"circa 1067","Llys Y Coed, Flintshire, Wales":"Llys Y Coed, Flintshire, Wales","Tegaingl, Flintshire, Wales":"Flintshire, Wales","Wales":"Wales","Flintshire, Wales":"Flintshire, Wales, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"about 1067–1118":"about 1067–1118","1065–1162":"1065–1162","1067–1118":"1067–1118","1070–1125":"1070–1125","1070–1139":"1070–1139","1075–1132":"1075–1132","1090–Female":"1090–Deceased","1110–Female":"1110–Deceased","1044–1105":"1044–1105","1048–1095":"1048–1095","1090":"1090","1044":"1044","1110":"1110","1132":"1132","1065":"1065","1064":"1064","1075":"1075","1162":"1162","1095":"1095","1070":"1070","1118":"1118","1139":"1139","1105":"1105","1048":"1048","1125":"1125","1067":"1067","about 1067":"about 1067","Llys Y Coed, Flintshire, Wales":"Llys Y Coed, Flintshire, Wales","Tegaingl, Flintshire, Wales":"Flintshire, Wales","Wales":"Wales","Flintshire, Wales":"Flintshire, Wales, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Owain","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: from the Middle English personal name <i>Swain</i>, <i>Swein</i> (Old Norse <i>Sveinn</i>, <i>Sven</i>, from <i>sveinn</i> ‘lad’).","English: occupational name from Middle English <i>swein</i> ‘servant, attendant; boy, young man’ (Old Norse <i>sveinn</i>). The word could also denote a swineherd or a peasant in general. The name was thoroughly confused with   Swan   1.","Irish: when not the English name, possibly an Anglicized form of <b>Mac Suibhne</b>; see   McSwain  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Swan","meanings":["English: occupational name from Middle English <i>swon(e)</i>, northern Middle English <i>swan(e)</i> ‘swineherd; peasant; male servant’ (Old English <i>swān</i>). Compare   Swain   2, with which this name was thoroughly confused.","English: occasionally perhaps a nickname from Middle English <i>swan</i>, <i>swon</i> ‘swan’. In the Middle Ages, the swan was taken as a symbol of false pride, and, according to Chaucer, jealousy. Compare   Kite  ,   Nightingale  , and   Pye  .","English: from the Middle English and Older Scots personal name <i>Swan</i>, an Anglicized form of Old Norse <i>Sveinn</i>. Compare   Swain   1."]},{"name":"Swainson","meanings":["English (northern): patronymic from the Middle English personal name <i>Swain</i> (Old Norse <i>Sveinn</i>; see   Swain  ) + <i>-son</i>. Compare   Swanson  .","English (northern): patronymic from Middle English <i>swein</i> ‘servant, attendant; boy, young man’ (Old Norse <i>sveinn</i>) + <i>-son</i>.","Americanized form of Swedish   Svensson   or of its cognate <b>Sveinsson</b>."]},{"name":"Swayne","meanings":["English: variant of   Swain  ."]},{"name":"Swaine","meanings":["English (Yorkshire): variant of   Swain  ."]}]},{"name":"Llewelyn","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Traditional: altered form (influenced by <i>llew</i> ‘lion’) of <i>Llywelyn</i>, an ancient name of uncertain derivation. It probably goes back to the Old Celtic name <i>Lugobelinos</i>, the first element of which is <i>Lugu-</i> (the name of a god;  see  Lleu  ); the second is a name-forming element found also in names such as <i>Cunobelinus</i> (<i>Cymbeline</i>). The name was borne by  Llywelyn ap Iorwerth  (  1173–1240 ) and his grandson Llywelyn ap Gruffydd (  d. 1282 ), Welsh princes who for a time united their countrymen in North Wales and led opposition to the power of the Norman barons in South Wales and the Marches."],"variants":[{"name":"Llywellyn","meanings":["Traditional: altered form (influenced by <i>llew</i> ‘lion’) of <i>Llywelyn</i>, an ancient name of uncertain derivation. It probably goes back to the Old Celtic name <i>Lugobelinos</i>, the first element of which is <i>Lugu-</i> (the name of a god;  see  Lleu  ); the second is a name-forming element found also in names such as <i>Cunobelinus</i> (<i>Cymbeline</i>). The name was borne by  Llywelyn ap Iorwerth  (  1173–1240 ) and his grandson Llywelyn ap Gruffydd (  d. 1282 ), Welsh princes who for a time united their countrymen in North Wales and led opposition to the power of the Norman barons in South Wales and the Marches."]},{"name":"Llywelyn","meanings":["(Welsh)  See  Llewelyn ."]},{"name":"Llewellyn","meanings":["See Lywelyn."]}]},{"name":"ab","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of any of the names beginning with this syllable."],"variants":[{"name":"Alexander","meanings":["From the Latin form of the Greek name <i>Alexandros</i>, from <i>alexein</i> ‘to defend’ + <i>anēr</i> ‘man, warrior’ (genitive <i>andros</i>). The name became extremely popular in the post-classical period, and was borne by several individuals in the New Testament and some early Christian saints. Its use as a common given name throughout Europe, however, derives largely from the fame of  Alexander the Great , King of Macedon (  356–323  bc  ), around whom a large body of popular legend grew up in late antiquity, much of which came to be embodied in the medieval ‘Alexander romances’."]},{"name":"Alan","meanings":["Of Celtic origin and uncertain derivation (possibly a diminutive of a word meaning ‘rock’). It was introduced into England by  Breton  followers of  William the Conqueror , most notably  Alan , Earl of Brittany, who was rewarded for his services with vast estates in the newly conquered kingdom. In Britain the variants  <b>Allan</b>  and  <b>Allen</b>  are considerably less frequent, and generally represent transferred uses of surname forms, whereas in America all three forms of the name are approximately equally common.  See also  Alun ."]},{"name":"Albert","meanings":["From an Old French name, <i>Albert</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to England, displacing the Old English form <i>Æþelbeorht</i>. The name is popular in a variety of forms in Western Europe, and has been traditional in a number of European princely families. It was out of favour in England for centuries, however, and the revival of its popularity in the 19th century was largely in honour of  Queen Victoria's  consort,  Prince Albert of Saxe-Coburg-Gotha ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Llewelyn ab Owain was born about 1067, in Flintshire, Wales, his father, Owain ab Edwin of Tegeingl, was 25 and his mother, Morwyl ferch Ednywain, was 20. He had at least 1 daughter. He died in 1118, at the age of 52."},"et":{"about 1067–1118":"umbes 1067–1118","1065–1162":"1065–1162","1067–1118":"1067–1118","1070–1125":"1070–1125","1070–1139":"1070–1139","1075–1132":"1075–1132","1090–Female":"1090–Surnud","1110–Female":"1110–Surnud","1044–1105":"1044–1105","1048–1095":"1048–1095